<h1>Tutorial 21. Assembling the Face of the Front Half of the Dress.</h1>
<p><strong>I join the layers of the prepared pieces by sewing along their vertical edges.</strong> I also make a short row of stitches along the horizontal edges. I stitch at a presser-foot width from the edge.</p>
<p><strong>Speaking about the princess seams of the back pieces, I start sewing from the seam allowance of the seam joining the main fabric pieces</strong> so as to leave the top lace part detached.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image014.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I sew together the layers of the cup pieces.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image020.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image022.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image024.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I sew over the reverse side of the other cup piece.</strong> The chiffon seems to settle better this way.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image026.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image028.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image030.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image032.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I even out the edges of the pieces.</strong> I trim the chiffon and the main fabric down to the edge of the batiste piece which serves as a standard.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image034.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I sew together the layers of the central cup piece.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image036.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image038.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image040.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image042.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image044.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image046.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image048.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>And I sew the lace overlay onto the central front piece of the body.</strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image050.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image052.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image054.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image056.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image058.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image060.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image062.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image064.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image066.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image068.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image070.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image072.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image074.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image076.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image078.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image080.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I even out the edges.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image082.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>All pieces are prepared now.</strong> I will pin and sew them together in the same sequence and manner as the lining pieces. All control joining points have also been transferred.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image084.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image086.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>You can hardly notice the joining seams underneath the lace overlay on the central front piece.</strong> It totally looks like one seamless piece!</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image088.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I pin the side front pieces to the central front piece in all control joining points and sew them together. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image090.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image092.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I also sew together the cup pieces, trim the seam allowances and press them open.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image094.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image096.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I have made a small mistake when I was working on the cups. Here is another proof that corset garments require 100% accuracy!</strong> I point it out in every teaching course. Of course, many defects come as a result of incorrectly taken measurements or miscalculated pattern adjustments, but a half of them are caused by carelessness in the sewing! <strong>Here is what happened to me.</strong> When I was pinning the cup pieces together along the princess seams, they were aligned perfectly from one side but from the other side there was a tiny mismatch of literally just some 4mm.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image098.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image100.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image102.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p>Instead of re-pinning that princess seam, I decided to leave it as it was. And guess what happened? <strong>The side cup piece got eased in!</strong> I couldn't fix it by pressing because the fabric is synthetic. As the result, the side piece looks �wavy".</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image103.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image105.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Besides, if you take a closer look at the princess seam line, you will notice that it resembles a zig zag rather than an even line.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image107.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The other princess seam is perfectly even.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image109.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p>Of course, we are talking perfectionism here. It is not like this defect will be noticeable from a couple of meters away. But it won't slip the attention of a demanding client. Besides, you won't be happy with a result like this anyway. This example is another proof that <strong>accuracy and thoroughness are crucial when you work on corset garments, particularly ones with a sophisticated design!</strong></p>
<p><strong>Time to get back to work though.</strong></p>
<p><strong>The corners of the cups and the central skirt piece must be aligned perfectly when joined with the central front piece.</strong> It helps to fold the central front piece in half and mark a dashed line at which the two corners are supposed to arrive.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image111.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image113.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I insert the cups and the central skirt piece in place.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image115.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p>It is a lot easier to sew in the cups than the skirt piece because the cups and the body of the dress have the same thickness.</p>
<p><strong>Joining the front of the dress with the central front piece of the skirt is a little challenging (particularly in the triangle area) </strong>because they have different thickness. Nevertheless, they meet very well thanks to the control joining points.</p>
<p><strong>Here are some tips:</strong> it doesn't matter from which side you pin the pieces together but you should stitch over the side where you notched the apex of the corner. Start by joining the pieces in the triangle area. Note that you are supposed to sew from down to up along one side and from up to down along the other side of the triangle. The key thing is to arrive precisely at the apex of the triangle.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image117.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image119.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image121.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image123.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I would also like to add a few words about the seam allowances.</strong></p>
<p>I will press them flat towards the bottom of the dress <strong>on the triangular part of the central skirt piece</strong>. In this case, there will be no tucks and the triangle won't sink in in the middle from the face side. <strong>On the cups,</strong> I press the bottom part of the seam allowance (before the princess seam) flat towards the bottom of the dress and the top part (after the princess seam) - flat and up onto the cup. This will enhance the shape of the cup.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image125.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image127.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Although the cup pieces were aligned very well,</strong> the princess seam which was not sewn neatly enough comes off from the center of the triangle. As you can see, one flaw brings about many consequences.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image129.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I press the front half of the dress and trim the seam allowances.</strong> There are many complicated areas on this dress, such as corners where you need to notch out excess fabric or arrange it in a particular way. For this reason, I highly recommend you press the garment before trimming the seam allowances.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image131.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%208/transcripts/Tutorial%2021_files/image133.jpg" alt=""></p>

